{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20907"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96968"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"12767"},{"type":"tags","id":"12768"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96968"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDown syndrome is a chromosomal condition characterized by distinctive physical features and various health considerations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most common genetic mechanism underlying Down syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meiotic nondisjunction resulting in trisomy 21","Uniparental disomy of chromosome 21","Robertsonian translocation involving chromosome 21","Mitotic nondisjunction during early embryogenesis","Deletion of the short arm of chromosome 21"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of Down syndrome is \u003Cstrong\u003Emeiotic nondisjunction resulting in trisomy 21\u003C/strong\u003E, accounting for approximately 95% of cases. This produces an extra copy of chromosome 21, giving affected individuals 47 chromosomes instead of 46. This nondisjunction occurs primarily during maternal meiosis, explaining why advanced maternal age correlates with higher Down syndrome rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUniparental disomy of chromosome 21\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when both copies of chromosome 21 come from one parent, maintaining the normal chromosome count without causing Down syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERobertsonian translocation involving chromosome 21\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 4% of Down syndrome cases, where chromosome 21\u0027s long arm attaches to another acrocentric chromosome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitotic nondisjunction during early embryogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E leads to mosaic Down syndrome (approximately 1% of cases), creating a mix of normal cells and cells with trisomy 21.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletion of the short arm of chromosome 21\u003C/strong\u003E causes a reduction in genetic material rather than an increase and is not associated with Down syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinical features of Down syndrome result from gene dosage effects and include characteristic facial features, intellectual disability, heart defects, higher leukaemia risk, and early-onset Alzheimer disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Down syndrome is most commonly caused by trisomy 21, resulting in 47 chromosomes instead of the normal 46.","The risk of Down syndrome increases with maternal age, with most cases involving nondisjunction during maternal meiosis.","About 4% of Down syndrome cases result from robertsonian translocations and 1% from mosaicism.","Down syndrome features include characteristic physical traits, intellectual disability, congenital heart defects, and early-onset Alzheimer disease."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 166-169"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T22:51:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T22:57:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13782"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96968"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10738"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chromosomal disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","update